description.text:
Alright bit of an update: Definitely strong enough, but be aware that the screws can come loose so either locktite them or check them every so often.

Couldnt really find any 2020 spool holders to go with the Parametric Universal Spool holder by rowokii (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:767317) so I made one up for my Tronxy x3 quickly. I printed it but haven't tested long term strength. The arm is 150mm long and forms (about) a 75 degree angle w.r.t. the x-axis, so if you want to calculate the force on it you can certainly do that. I will say it feels solid and I doubt it will break.

There are two versions. Counter bored mounting holes and non. Unnecessary maybe but the option is there. basically its the difference of 5mm of plastic vs 3mm holding the thing on. I made the counter bore version to use extra 4x8mm screws from my kit, but the non version "should" be stronger.

Designed to be printed with minimal support and maximum bed adherence.

Any questions or comments let me know, if it worked for you let me know, if not I'm glad to hear how it could be better. This is my first design im releasing and I've only been using fusion for a few weeks, so I am always open to suggestion!

Additional Parts need:
Any spool holder that uses a 5/8" threaded rod.
4x 4mm (choose your length accordingly but probably between 8-15mm length should work depending on version)
4x 4mm t-nut

P.S. probably obvious but make sure you lay it flat lol.

An extremely rough logo of The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild. I say rough because the mesh isn't perfect, but it will print on most printers given you are printing it at a sufficient size and quality to allow fine thin details to show.

The rugged nature of the mesh actually makes it look rugged like the logo, which is kinda neat.

If you are printing, you can adjust how embossed the text is by adjusting the Z scale. Also, you can adjust how thick the back piece the lettering stands on is by adjusting the z height- allowing it to clip into the ground will make it thinner, saving you filament.

The model is offered as is and probably won't be refined. If I felt like it, I'd make it from scratch and make it nice. As of now, the mesh was generated using some image to mesh software found online.

description.text:
This is a notch width test pattern, with notches cut into both sides from 0.100" to 0.150" wide in 0.01" steps. The idea, obviously, is to straddle the 1/8" or 0.125" nominal thickness of the material.
Since 0.01" should be on the same order of magnitude as the kerf (material lost to the laser's cut), I didn't think we needed more precision.

I'm not sure how engraving works, so you may need to adjust the text labels in the design to fit your laser's requirements. Other than that, here's how I would use this, but I'm sure there are other possibilities:
  • Cut this pattern in the same material you plan to use. If you have the room, I would suggest sticking it in the corner of a prototype design. It won't help with that cut, but it could help the next one.
  • Once the test pattern is cut, try sliding a scrap piece of the material in the notches until you find the one with the snuggest fit.
  • Read the value engraved next to the chosen notch. This is not the real width of the cut but the width that notch was in Inkscape or your software package of choice.
  • Adjust your design to use notches of that chosen width in same software package. Easiest way with an existing design with 1/8" notches would be to scale the entire design appropriately, e.g. if you chose 0.121" your design needs to be scaled to 0.121/0.125 or 0.968.
    • If you disagree with the math, or have another comment/suggestion, comments are welcome. This is Public Domain, so you can also modify it to your heart's content.

Inspiration

This was actually a school assignment and it was my second succulent planter, but this one needed to meet a few more requirements. I liked the polygon style of the other one so I decided to continue that style but in order to make my job easier I made it a hexagon instead of a pentagon.

Design Process

I extruded a hexagon and then made another smaller one to BooleanDifference the object and make a container out of it. I then added a rim to the bottom and an indention for that rim on the top, making these planters stackable and easier to store. I then added to attachment modules that slide into one another, allowing the pieces to each be attached to another planter, making it possible to design shapes and even stair like structures.

description.text:
I printed the previous poly snaps and was frustrated by the friction fit joints that seemed to need ultra-precision to print. I attempted them several times and they were either too tight to even go together or so loose they fell apart.

So I used blender to add spherical nubs and sockets that give the parts some extra tolerance and a snap when you get them together. It isn't a perfect solution, but I think it helps.

Also I noticed the original poly snaps were limited to +-90 degree angle. This version can do a full 270 degree folding completely flat on one side. Without this addition, the red/green/blue piece in the picture would have simply been impossible.

I made these primarily for a coworker of mine. One of the neat things he noticed is that you don't actually need the squares, pentagons, hexagons... as these can actually be made from the triangles! See the green and white sphere.

I was able to print over 700 of these for just under $10, in material. In a batch of 52 I had between 1-3 lift off the build plate which ruined them, but still had around 50/print successful over the 15 prints!

Enjoy!!!

EDIT: I have added two more versions. These have more space between the teeth so they snap together easier. Print two if each type to see which works best for you!

description.text: I made this Kanji Nihon stamp for fun. It is a quick print and easy to fix to a dowel. I was unable to upload a modifiable Tinker Cad model but it is really easy to make it say anything. The stamp quality is not very clean. It looks more like a wood block stamp. If you are looking to make a unique stamp I could probably help. A flexible filament would probably be best but I haven't used it yet.

Printer:

Monoprice Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

I just printed it face up.

Sanding

I sanded the surface carefully to make sure that I got as much surface contact as possible went applying ink to the stamp and also when stamping the paper. I placed sand paper on a table and dragged it across several times.

The Handle

Next I cut an approximately 30 mm long piece of 3/8" dowel to act as the handle. I then glued the stamp to the dowel end using regular white craft glue. I didn't print the handle because it made my print time almost an hour.

Design

I designed this in Tinker Cad by using the text example and rotated it 180 degrees to make the text backwards. Then I just copied the Japanese from Google Translate and pasted it in the Tinker Cad prompt. The outer circle is a tube placed over the base cylinder. The diameters are the same (1 cm). The base cylinder is about 2 mm shorter than the outer tube. I then centered the text and made it the same height as the outer cylinder. The height of the entire model is about 5 mm. I had to download it as an STL several times and simulate in Cura to make sure that details were not missing from the text. Letters would disappear with too many characters.

The boarder, text, and revolvers are raised 3mm above the base. So, if you pause and switch to a contrasting filament for the last few layers it will realy make the buckle stand out.

This model is designed to protect your camera body and screen. The little "window" allows to verify that your camera is recording or not.

I will do some upgrades to this model on future (different angles and less weight).

remixed_from.title: Desktop USB and SD Card Stand

description.text: This is a remix of a model by bekira. I wanted to make this model because it was smaller than the other ones that I found on Thingiverse. I only have a few SD cards right now. I just needed to scale it and modify it a little for size.

Printer:

Monoprice Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.175 Layer height

Infill:

0%

Hole Size

I needed to file the USB holes a little. I think that this was mainly due to the quality that I printed at.

Design

I wanted to make the original model but for some reason the STL file was 8 mm long! I scaled it up by 10 in Tinker CAD and that seemed to be correct. While I was in cad I trimmed off the stabilizing feet because it took up too much space.
